![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/2619299d-b866-4cae-91c4-c4fd654abc6d/15495.jpg)

Boxing legends Mike Tyson and Floyd Mayweather have reportedly signed a deal to square off in an exhibition match scheduled for the spring of 2026. According to TMZ Sports, the bout will be promoted by CSI Sports/Fight Sports, setting the stage for a clash between two of the most iconic figures in boxing history.

While a specific date and venue are still to be determined, the confirmation of the fight has already sent shockwaves through the sports world. Tyson, despite a sometimes-turbulent relationship with Mayweather over the years, is said to be thrilled about the upcoming event. The match will be an exhibition, ensuring that Mayweather's perfect 50-0 professional record remains out of jeopardy.

Unfazed by the challenge, Mayweather expressed his signature confidence. "I've been doing this for 30 years and there hasn't been a single fighter that can tarnish my legacy," Mayweather said. "You already know that if I am going to do something, it's going to be big and it’s going to be legendary. I'm the best in the business of boxing. This exhibition will give the fans what they want."